    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div id="faq-container">

        <details>
          <summary>How accurate is a laser range finder?</summary>
          <p>Most consumer laser range finders are incredibly accurate, typically within plus or minus 1 yard (or 1 meter) for outdoor sporting models like those used in golf or hunting. Construction-grade Laser Distance Meters used indoors are even more precise, often accurate to within 1/16th or 1/32nd of an inch.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Does a range finder work at night?</summary>
          <p>Yes, laser range finders work perfectly fine in the dark because they emit and detect their own invisible infrared light; they do not rely on ambient visible light. However, you still need to be able to see the target through the viewfinder to aim the laser, which is why some high-end models feature illuminated internal displays.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>What is 'slope' on a golf range finder?</summary>
          <p>'Slope' is a feature that uses an internal inclinometer to measure the angle of incline or decline to the target. It then calculates an adjusted 'plays like' distance. For example, a flag that is 150 yards away but significantly uphill might 'play like' 165 yards. This feature is usually illegal in official tournament play but great for practice.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Can rain or fog affect my range finder?</summary>
          <p>Yes. Heavy rain, fog, or snow can scatter the infrared laser beam, causing the device to read the distance to the precipitation rather than your actual target. While some premium hunting range finders have software modes to help ignore near-field obstructions, severe weather will significantly reduce the maximum range of any device.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>What is the difference between a golf range finder and a hunting range finder?</summary>
          <p>Golf range finders are optimized to pick up small, highly reflective targets (the flag prism) against cluttered backgrounds and often feature 'Target Lock' vibration. Hunting range finders prioritize distant, non-reflective targets (like animals) and often feature 'Brush Mode' to ignore close-up branches, as well as angle compensation for shooting from tree stands.</p>
        </details>

      </div>
    </section>
